<br>
My suggestion for a 80 gig drive (that means it's just a suggestion, feel free to flame it)<br>
<br>
One partition (2-4 gig) called &quot;Work&quot;. Install what you need to do serious work there (like MS Office, Online Banking software etc.). Don't fiddle around with that partition too much. It is used only to do &quot;work&quot;. Also secure this setup with a personal firewall and a virus scanner.<br>
<br>
One partition (10-20 gig) called &quot;Games&quot;. Install all your games (except EQ hehe) there. This is the partition to try on new things. Demos, games, shareware and other stuff goes here. If the partition is screwed up (sooner or later hehe), reformat and install what you need.<br>
<br>
One partition (2-4 gig) called &quot;EverQuest&quot;. Try to find the best OS for EQ (I would say 2k, although XP or 98 might work). Install only the bare necessities like gfx driver, audio driver and DirectX. Hide all other partitions here. The trick is, that you don't need a firewall here as there is no data available for hackers when on that partition :-)<br>
<br>
One partition (40 gig) for &quot;Data&quot;: Put all data here that you need for the work partition (applications and data). This partition is ONLY visible from the work partition, not from the game or EQ partition.<br>
<br>
Rest is free space. You can use it to &quot;test&quot; a new OS or whatever.<br>
<br>
For the bootmanager I suggest VAMOS (www.vamos.de). It's a nifty tool, shareware and works smoothly. It makes the hiding of partitions really easy.<br>
<br>
I know it's a lot of work, but my system is setup like this and I wouldn't want to miss it. It mixes some security (hidden data partition), ease of use (game partition that is replacable in a jiffy) and variety (reserved space for tests, EQ for long sessions etc.).<br>
<br>
